          "name": "Mihir Hurwanth",
          "role": "PhD Researcher at Queen Mary University of London",
          "description": "AI is transforming drug discovery by learning patterns across chemistry, biology, and evolution, enabling faster and more targeted identification of promising compounds. My work sits inside that shift by showing how machine learning can make natural product discovery more semantic and more deeply informed. My journey here began in biochemistry, where I learned to view molecules as living stories: shaped by enzymes, evolution, and environment. During my MSc in Artificial Intelligence for Drug Discovery, that perspective shifted toward a computational approach. I worked on RNN-based generative models trained with reinforcement learning to design novel compounds. I developed a deep interest in how model architectures, scoring functions, and chemical constraints influence AI's creativity in molecular design. Now, my research focuses on applying those ideas to the natural-products domain. I develop data pipelines that combine ecological, chemotaxonomic, and phylogenetic data into structured inputs for machine learning models. This helps me map chemical space across extensive plant lineages, discover overlooked species with potential biosynthetic abilities, and employ generative techniques to suggest molecules based on nature’s own design principles. What motivates me is the potential to connect two worlds that rarely intersect — global biodiversity patterns and the detailed logic of drug discovery. By learning from how plants have tackled chemical challenges over millions of years, I aim to create tools that make early-stage discovery more predictive, more interpretable, and more aligned with the biology that underpins human health.",
